ē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Thornton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Scottish: habitational name from any of numerous places throughout England and Scotland so called, from Old English <i>thorn</i> ‘thorn tree’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. The placename is most frequent in northern England, especially Yorkshire, where there are at least 16 possible sources for the surname.","Irish: Anglicized (translated) form of Gaelic <b>Mac Sceacháin</b> ‘son of <i>Sceachán</i>’ (see   Skehan  ).","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Draighneáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Draighneán</i>’ (see   Drennan  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Thornber","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of the five minor places in Yorkshire called Thornber, particularly Thornber in Halton West. The placenames derive from Old English <i>thorn</i> ‘thorn’ + <i>beorg</i> ‘hill, mound’.","Irish: adopted for various Irish names containing an element meaning ‘thorn’; compare   Thornton  ."]},{"name":"Thorton","meanings":["(1997: 465;2007: 2025; 2010: NA)","English: probably a shortened form of   Thornton  , or a habitational name from Thorton in Marnhull, Dorset, which has the same origin."]},{"name":"Skehan","meanings":["Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Sceacháin</b> or <b>Ó Sceacháin</b> ‘son (or descendant) of <i>Sceachán</i>’, a personal name probably based on a diminutive of <i>sceach</i> ‘briar, thorn bush’. The Gaelic name has sometimes been ‘translated’ as   Thornton  ."]}]},{"name":"Margery","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["The usual medieval vernacular form of   Margaret   (now also commonly spelled   Marjorie  ). This form of the name is preserved in the nursery rhyme ‘See-saw, Margery Daw’."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":29,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":38,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Lady Margery de Thornton was born about 1186, in Thornton Mayow, Cheshire, England, her father, Sir Randle Baron Thornton of Thornton-Le-Moors le Roter de Thornton, was 25 and her mother, Amicia De Kingsley, was 11184. She had at least 1 son with Sir William de Brereton. She died about 1240, in Cheshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 56."},"et":{"about 1186–about 1240":"umbes 1186–umbes 1240","1186–1240":"1186–1240","1180–1120":"1180–1120","–1250":"–1250","1162–1244":"1162–1244","1172–1244":"1172–1244","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1244":"1244","1120":"1120","1186":"1186","1240":"1240","1162":"1162","1250":"1250","1172":"1172","about 1240":"umbes 1240","about 1186":"umbes 1186","1180":"1180","Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Thornton Mayow, Cheshire, England":"Thornton Mayow, Cheshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1186–about 1240":"noin 1186–noin 1240","1186–1240":"1186–1240","1180–1120":"1180–1120","–1250":"–1250","1162–1244":"1162–1244","1172–1244":"1172–1244","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1244":"1244","1120":"1120","1186":"1186","1240":"1240","1162":"1162","1250":"1250","1172":"1172","about 1240":"noin 1240","about 1186":"noin 1186","1